    <h1 class="page-title">Recollimation shocks</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Recollimation shocks</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Type:</th><td>Research</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Educational level:</th><td>Research</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Key Papers:</th><td><WikiLink slug="pages/Bromberg_2011" text="Bromberg et al. (2011)" />, Peretti et al. (2603.16647)</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Recollimation shocks</strong> occur when an expanding jet is squeezed by external pressure (for example, from a cocoon) causing the flow to converge and form a standing shock. These shocks are often oblique to the jet axis and can be quasi-stationary over long times.</p>

    <h2>Physical description</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Geometry</strong> — The shock surface is typically conical or parabolic; obliquity (angle with respect to flow) controls compression and downstream pressure.</li>
      <li><strong>Strength</strong> — Even highly inclined recollimation shocks can be strong if the upstream Mach number is high and the cocoon pressure is sufficient.</li>
      <li><strong>DSA at recollimation shocks</strong> — Despite obliquity, DSA can operate efficiently if turbulence scatters particles across the shock; confinement and diffusion regime set E_max.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why this matters</h2>
    <p>Peretti et al. (2603.16647) show that recollimation shocks in sub-relativistic jets are viable cosmic-ray accelerators, predicting source-class-dependent maximum energies (protostars → TeV; microquasars → tens of PeV; Seyferts → PeV–EeV under optimistic turbulence). Understanding recollimation shocks links jet dynamics to high-energy signatures in cocoons and surrounding media.</p>

    <h2>Key references</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Bromberg et al. 2011 — analytic jet–cocoon framework used to locate recollimation shocks.</li>
      <li>Peretti et al. 2603.16647 — study of DSA at recollimation shocks in sub-relativistic jets.</li>
    </ol>

